body:
{'Refactor passport to conform to jshint settings.
Remove html extension on FCC links in challenge 

fixes https://github.com/FreeCodeCamp/freecodecamp/issues/6 
'}

{"I know I entered massage therapist as most recent job on the initial form,
but that was two years ago. Plus, afterwards, I realized that writing a book for
a publisher counts as most recent job (I forget about freelance stuff sometimes)!
Also removed part about Hypercard because I figure most code campers
won't know what I was referring to.
"}
{'Fixes email signup/signin issues and angularizes the email signup form. Also adds unique username check to profile.jade.\n'}
{'Solve email login issues, angularize forms to extreme measures, prettify and give feedback in real time.\n'}
{"I'm not 100% sure that this is the same book, but I tried to find something I thought was similar.\n"}
{"the django book is extremely out of date. I'll find some better free django books but until then removal is best\n"}
{'Fixed .NET (C# / VB / Nemerle / Visual Studio) anchor link.\n'}
{'Added my published book "97 Things Every Programmer Should Know - Extended" from LeanPub, which is available for free download.\n'}
{'An open sourced book written by Dr. Charles Severance, professor at MichUni. The book is available in every possible format, a really great read!\n'}
{'Included free book by O’Reilly Media to JavaScript.\n'}
{'It looks like the author copy/pasted the awesome-go repo - removed some stuff and then replaced "go" with "cobol".\n'}
{"Initial pass at adding categories and additional API's!\n"}
{'OpenWeatherMap is a very useful weather data service! \n'}
{'Added the [Belgian transport API](https://hello.irail.be/api/)\n'}
{'Jeff Dean Video\n'}
{'yah!\n'}

{'This pull-request fixes bug in the Markdown parser used by GitHub to translate `[x]` into HTML checkboxes, the way it is currently written makes the transpiler believe that the text in between parenthesis is actually part of a Markdown link with this syntax `[title](href)` which makes me believe that the parser is taking `/\[x\][^(]+\([^)]+\)/` _(notice the pattern in between the braces and the parenthesis)_.

So instead of this:
- [x] _(very dated)_ http://dondodge.typepad.com/the_next_big_thing/2010/09/how-to-get-a-job-at-google-interview-questions-hiring-process.html

... it is rendering this:
- [x](very dated) http://dondodge.typepad.com/the_next_big_thing/2010/09/how-to-get-a-job-at-google-interview-questions-hiring-process.html
'}
{'Improving readability and making a cleaner template.\nIf you agree with the changes I can follow finishing the file.\n'}
{"Updating readability up to L1007.\nI hope I didn't break any link with a typo.\n"}
{'Oops.\n'}
{'Done. :)\nAgain, I hope nothing was broken by some typo.\n'}
{'I reviewed the entire file more cautiously and I think those were the only typos.\n'}

{'Add a section for how to create a demoscene demo. Some of the links are not exactly tutorials, but IMO, neccessary pointers and introductions that are neccessary to get an idea about what a demoscene demo is, for uninitiated developers.'}
{"This is a collection of three blog posts, but I've linked to only Part I in this PR and readers can follow on from there (links to consecutive parts are available at the end of each blog post)."}
{'Add link to [Parser Combinator](https://github.com/gosukiwi/parser-combinator) library for Ruby'}

{'For example:
- Frontend -> Front-end
- PHP-7 -> PHP 7
- Node JS -> Node.js
- NPM -> npm

And so on, in general, the names have been renamed in such a way as they are used officially.

Maybe it does not really matter, but still I want to use the correct technology names, so that there is no confusion'}
{'Really like what you did. I added a few things that I think are important for devs to keep an eye on.'}

{'Related: #12 #24 
Adds:

- [x] Xdebug to PHP (Backend)
- [x] Byebug to Ruby (Backend)
- [x] Material Design to CSS Frameworks (Frontend)'}
{'Add loopback.io to javascript section and Zend to PHP 7 section'}
{'I added New Relic to the list of monitoring tools. Is there a better way to monitor your infrastructure?'}
{'expanding .net to asp.net and asp.net core'}
{'Added Zend Framework as an option under PHP frameworks.\r\n\r\nCheers! :)'}
{'As proposed in issue #32'}
{'Video discusses the current trends of web-development technologies and answers an important question - What to be learned in 2017 .'}
{'A small fix to change to drop the "a" in "solving a many interview questions".'}
{'Small typo in the Remote Procedure Call section.\r\ns/definied/defined'}
{'There should be whitespaces between the western characters and Chinese characters.'}
{'英文不是很好，先有个初版，法律部分是找的中国商务部2007年对外发布的英文版劳动法的第41条 [英文版本](http://english.mofcom.gov.cn/aarticle/policyrelease/internationalpolicy/200703/20070304475283.html,)。'}
{'add English version'}
{'网址： [https://996.icu/#/zh_CN](https://996.icu/#/zh_CN)'}
{'website'}
{'其实最好应该再加一个俄罗斯文版本的国际歌歌词。'}

{'This is not blocking the initial launch, so feel free to put it on the back-burner for now.

The Jasmine test harness still runs in the parent window and reports to PhantomJS via `window.callPhantom`, but each test `<iframe>` has its own copy of `react-test.js` and each individual test module is required in the global context of a separate `<iframe>`.

This gives us a significant approximation of the benefits of mocking, at least in terms of isolating tests from one another.

cr @jeffmo @zpao
'}
{'The buttons on the index were pointing at wrong paths.\n'}
{'Added some additional examples to explain common usage patterns for custom events.\n'}
{'Whenever you have a spare moment =]\n'}

{"I messed this up pretty badly and didn't include react _at all_.

Test Plan: npm pack && npm install <packed.tgz>, then require('react-tools')`

Fixes #10
"}
